The species that manufactured stone tools include the genus Homo, specifically Homo habilis, Homo erectus, and Homo heidelbergensis. The earliest evidence of stone tool use dates back to around 2.6 million years ago during the Oldowan period, with examples such as Olduvai Chopper, discovered in Tanzania.

Other species that used stone tools include Australopithecus afarensis, who utilized simple stone tools around 3.9-2.9 million years ago in East Africa. In addition, early members of the genus Paranthropus, such as Paranthropus robustus and Paranthropus boisei, also used stone tools during their existence.

Extinct species of the genus Homo that manufactured stone tools include Homo ergaster, Homo neanderthalensis (also known as Neanderthals), and early members of Homo sapiens in Africa, around 300,000 years ago. Other extinct human species that used stone tools include Denisovans and Homo floresiensis.

In some parts of the world, other primates like chimpanzees and bonobos have been observed using simple stone tools to crack open nuts or seeds.

The human heart is a vital organ that pumps blood throughout the body, and it is composed of four main chambers: 

the right atrium, 
the left atrium, 
the right ventricle, 
and the left ventricle.

These chambers work together to circulate oxygenated and deoxygenated blood. The right atrium receives oxygen-depleted blood from the body through the superior and inferior vena cavae. The blood then flows into the right ventricle, which pumps it into the pulmonary arteries for transport to the lungs for oxygenation.

From there, the oxygen-rich blood returns to the heart in the pulmonary veins and enters the left atrium. This chamber then contracts and pushes the blood into the left ventricle, which is responsible for pumping it out of the heart and into the aorta, the largest artery in the body, supplying oxygenated blood to the rest of the body.
